In Encryption & Decryption you can use a private and a public key. When you encrypt the data with a private key
then you have to decrypt  with a public key and the opposite

For example, when 'A' want to send a message to 'B' will use the public key of 'B' to encrypt and when the B
receive the message it will use it's private key to decrypt it. SO, 'C' can't read the message because don't hve the private key of B
Problem: 'C' can hack the message from 'A', decrypt it with B's public key, change it, and send it to B. So, B can't understand that the message is
from C and not from A
Solution --> 'A' will encrypt the message with his own private key instead(instead B's public key because C can use it also). After that, message goes to
B and B can decrypt it with only one way: A's public key(because it was encrypted with A's private key). If the decryption is possible it means that only A could have sent it.
--> If 'C' can decrypt it with A's public key and encrypt it with his own private key. But when it comes to B, B can not decrypt it with A's public key, so something is wrong(it is not coming from A)

But one problem here: we don't have security here. Only the proof who sent the message and anyone can read data
For that reason we have double encryption


** Double encryption
'A' want to send a message to 'B' and uses B's public key to encrypt(first layer done). Then, the same packet will encrypted again with A's private key.
When the message arrives at B, it decrypt it with A's public key(that is also a proof that A sent it) and package is still encrypted. Now, B uses it's own private key to do
the second decryption

